::Mandatory:: (link: https://cdn.intra.42.fr/pdf/pdf/188792/en.subject.pdf)
	- GENERAL:
		* types:
			#NOTE: not clear if all coefficients are supposed to be rational numbers
			rational numbers (does it get its own class?)
			complex numbers (with rational coefficients)
			Matrices
			Polynomial equations of degrees less than or equal to 2
		* Assignment of en expression to a variable by type inference
		* Reassignment of an existing variable with an expression of another type
		* Resolution of a mathematical expression with or without defined variable (s)
		* Resolution of an equation of degree less than or equal to 2
		* Operations between types, as much as possible. (Probably matrix mul, scalar * matrice etc)
		* Exit the program itself (by keyword, signal, keyboard shortcut, ...)
	- ASSIGNMENT PART:
		* Rational numbers (for any x ∈ Q)
		* maginary numbers for any x = a + ib such as (a, b) ∈ Q^2
		* Matrices for any A ∈ Mn,p(Q)
		* Functions (with only one variable) // I am assuming no complex numbers for functions coefficients
		* Must be able to reassign a variable and change the type of variable by inference.
		* Must be able to reassign the result of a computation to a variable
	- COMPUTATIONAL PART:
		* operations:
			1. mul: '*'
			2. div: '/'
			3. plus: '+'
			4. minus: '−'
			5. mod: '%'
			6. matrix mul: '**'
			7. power of integer and positive (zero included): '^'
		* Must handle parentheses and computation priorities
		* Set a function/variable then '= ?' should be used to return the value of this variable in the context of the program.
		* The resolution of a computation is symbolized by the '?' operator at the end of the input
		* Manage image resolution (ie. f(2), when f(x) = 2x+59)
		* It will also have to manage the computation of the square roots of polynomials when the
			degree is less than or equal to 2, proposing solutions in R or C.
				funA(x) = x^2 + 2x + 1
				x^2 + 2x + 1
				> y = 0
				0
				> funA(x) = y ?
				x^2 + 2x + 1 = 0
				One solution in R:
				-1

	- SYNTAX:
		* Variable/Function names: only letters + case insensitive. No variable can be called i
		* Each input validation: display value stored in the variable
			Expressions must be simplified when possible (e.g., (x2 + 3x + 2)/(x + 1) = x + 2 and 2×5 = 10).
		* 'xx' != x^2 but a variable named xx
		* Matrix: [[A0,0, A0,1, ...]; [A1,0, A1,1, ...]; ...]
			The semicolon is used to separate the rows of a matrix, so it is not present in the assignment of
			a matrix that has only one row. On the other hand, the comma is used to separate the columns of a
			matrix, which on the other hand will not be present in the assignment of a matrix that has only one column.
		* Functions: functionName(variable)
::BONUS::
	- Function curve display
	- more functions: exp(x), sqrt(x), abs(x), cos(x), sin(x), tan(x), cot(x), ...
	- Radian computation for angles
	- Function composition: F(G(x))
	- Norm computation
	- Display stored variables
	- History of commands + results
	- Matrix inversion
	- add vectors
	- whatever i want


::PLAN::
	- Lexer: transform the input into tokens
		* tokens:
			° number
			° plus
			° minus
			° multiplication
			° division
			° parentheses ('(', ')')
			° EOF
			° invalid
			° matrix mul ('**')
			° mod ('%')
			° i (imaginary)
			° assign ('=')
			° query ('?')
			° comma (',')
			° semicolon (';')
			° square brackets ('[', ']')
			° identifier (alpha digit not accepted)
			° power ('^')


	- Parser: transform the tokens into an abstract syntax tree
		* Grammar:
			statement :=
				  assignment
				| function_definition
				| expression

			assignment :=
				IDENT '=' expression

			function_definition :=
				IDENT '(' IDENT ')' '=' expression

			expression :=
				term (('+' | '-') term)*

			term :=
				factor (('*' | '/') factor)*

			factor :=
				  NUMBER
				| IDENT
				| '(' expression ')'
